  "doc_id": "6545",
  "text": "The development of triazine resistance in crop plants is an attractive goal because of the potential benefits it offers for weed control. The loss of vigor that accompanies the resistance trait, however, is a serious drawback. Studies with nearly isogenic resistant and susceptible lines of Brassica napus L. revealed that resistant plants grew more slowly (JJ Hart, unpublished data; 5) and had a lower photon yield [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] than susceptible plants. Development of productive resistant crop varieties will depend on our understanding of the molecular mechanism that brings about the loss of photosynthetic performance and growth in plants with the resistance trait.",
